what that measures is the proportion of students&nbsp;
who answered an item correctly. The higher&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:30.480 --> 00:00:36.960
the value the greater the proportion of students&nbsp;who
responded to an item correctly. The lower the value&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:36.960 --> 00:00:43.840
indicates that fewer students got the question&nbsp;
correct. Those values are also known as p-values&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:45.200 --> 00:00:52.400
a difficulty index or p-value of equal to or&nbsp;
greater than 70 percent means your question would&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:52.400 --> 00:01:00.720
be considered easy to very easy. If your p-value&nbsp;
is in the mid-range of equal to or less than 30&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:01.600 --> 00:01:07.600
then you're in the difficulty range&nbsp;
for values equal to or less than 30&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:08.800 --> 00:01:11.840
That means your question falls&nbsp;
within the range of very difficult

00:01:14.320 --> 00:01:20.880
For exam questions that have p-values&nbsp;
of 90 or higher or 20 and lower&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:21.440 --> 00:01:27.760
consider adjusting your questions or not using&nbsp;
them at all in future exams. For example on those&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:27.760 --> 00:01:33.440
90 or higher items consider restructuring&nbsp;
your questions' lead-in or distractors&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:34.400 --> 00:01:40.320
On those 20 percent or lower items review&nbsp;
them for possible confusing language or&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:40.320 --> 00:01:44.720
perhaps it's a topic you may want to&nbsp;
amend in your future class instruction

00:01:47.520 --> 00:01:53.200
